                <head>No. 457.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Phelps</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Frelinghuysen</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-10-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">October</hi> 24, 1883</date>. (Received November
                        17.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 21.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Mr. Iglesias came in yesterday afternoon from
                    Ancon. The city was gay with bunting, householders being required to display
                    flags.</p>
                <p>A large crowd assembled to see the arrival, and the event upon the whole may be
                    considered favorable.</p>
                <p>I have not yet received the copy of the principal articles of the treaty of
                    peace. It has been promised since Monday by a friend of Mr. Iglesias, and some
                    difficulty apparently attends procuring it.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>S. L. PHELPS.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
